# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geospatial-gis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Modern cartography constitutes many theoretical and practical foundations of geographic information systems (GIS) and geographic information science (GISc).
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] What is the earliest known map is a matter of some debate, both because the term "map" is not well-defined and because some artifacts that might be maps might actually be something else.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] A wall painting that might depict the ancient Anatolian city of Çatalhöyük (previously known as Catal Huyuk or Çatal Hüyük) has been dated to the late 7th millennium BCE.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Among the prehistoric alpine rock carvings of Mount Bego (France) and Valcamonica (Italy), dated to the 4th millennium BCE, geometric patterns consisting of dotted rectangles and lines are widely interpreted in archaeological literature as depicting cultivated plots.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Other known maps of the ancient world include the Minoan "House of the Admiral" wall painting from c.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] 1600 BCE, showing a seaside community in an oblique perspective, and an engraved map of the holy Babylonian city of Nippur, from the Kassite period (14th – 12th centuries BCE).
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The oldest surviving world maps are from 9th century BCE Babylonia.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] One shows Babylon on the Euphrates, surrounded by Assyria, Urartu and several cities, all, in turn, surrounded by a "bitter river" (Oceanus).
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Another depicts Babylon as being north of the center of the world.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The ancient Greeks and Romans created maps from the time of Anaximander in the 6th century BCE.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the 2nd century CE, Ptolemy wrote his treatise on cartography, Geographia.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] This contained Ptolemy's world map – the world then known to Western society (*Ecumene*).
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] As early as the 8th century, Arab scholars were translating the works of the Greek geographers into Arabic.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Roads were essential in the Roman world, motivating the creation of maps, called *itinerarium*, that portrayed the world as experienced via the roads.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The *Tabula Peutingeriana* is the only surviving example.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In ancient China, geographical literature dates to the 5th century BCE.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The oldest extant Chinese maps come from the State of Qin, dated back to the 4th century BCE, during the Warring States period.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the book *Xin Yi Xiang Fa Yao*, published in 1092 by the Chinese scientist Su Song, a star map on the equidistant cylindrical projection.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Although this method of charting seems to have existed in China even before this publication and scientist, the greatest significance of the star maps by Su Song is that they represent the oldest existent star maps in printed form.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Early forms of cartography of India included depictions of the pole star and surrounding constellations.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] These charts may have been used for navigation.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The Arab geographer Muhammad al-Idrisi produced his medieval atlas *Tabula Rogeriana (Book of Roger)* in 1154.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Along with the substantial text he had written, he created a world map influenced mostly by the Ptolemaic conception of the world, but with significant influence from multiple Arab geographers.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] It remained the most accurate world map for the next three centuries.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The map was divided into seven climatic zones, with detailed descriptions of each zone.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] As part of this work, a smaller, circular map depicting the south on top and Arabia in the center was made.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Al-Idrisi also made an estimate of the circumference of the world, accurate to within 10%.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the Age of Discovery, from the 15th century to the 17th century, European cartographers both copied earlier maps (some of which had been passed down for centuries) and drew their own based on explorers' observations and new surveying techniques.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The invention of the magnetic compass, telescope and sextant enabled increasing accuracy.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In 1492, Martin Behaim, a German cartographer and advisor to the king John II of Portugal, made the oldest extant globe of the Earth.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In 1507, Martin Waldseemüller produced a globular world map and a large 12-panel world wall map (*Universalis Cosmographia*) bearing the first use of the name "America." Portuguese cartographer Diogo Ribero was the author of the first known planisphere with a graduated Equator (1527).
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Italian cartographer Battista Agnese produced at least 71 manuscript atlases of sea charts.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Johannes Werner refined and promoted the Werner projection.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] This was an equal-area, heart-shaped world map projection (generally called a cordiform projection) that was used in the 16th and 17th centuries.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Over time, other iterations of this map type arose; most notable are the sinusoidal projection and the Bonne projection.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The Werner projection places its standard parallel at the North Pole; a sinusoidal projection places its standard parallel at the equator; and the Bonne projection is intermediate between the two.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In 1569, mapmaker Gerardus Mercator first published a map based on his Mercator projection, which uses equally-spaced parallel vertical lines of longitude and parallel latitude lines spaced farther apart as they get farther away from the equator.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] By this construction, courses of constant bearing are conveniently represented as straight lines for navigation.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The same property limits its value as a general-purpose world map because regions are shown as increasingly larger than they actually are the further from the equator they are.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Mercator is also credited as the first to use the word "atlas" to describe a collection of maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the later years of his life, Mercator resolved to create his Atlas, a book filled with many maps of different regions of the world, as well as a chronological history of the world from the Earth's creation by God until 1568.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] He was unable to complete it to his satisfaction before he died.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Still, some additions were made to the Atlas after his death, and new editions were published after his death.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In 1570, the Brabantian cartographer Abraham Ortelius, strongly encouraged by Gillis Hooftman, created the first true modern atlas, *Theatrum Orbis Terrarum.* In a rare move, Ortelius credited mapmakers who contributed to the atlas, the list of which grew to 183 individuals by 1603.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the Renaissance, maps were used to impress viewers and establish the owner's reputation as sophisticated, educated, and worldly.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Because of this, towards the end of the Renaissance, maps were displayed with equal importance of painting, sculptures, and other pieces of art.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the sixteenth century, maps were becoming increasingly available to consumers through the introduction of printmaking, with about 10% of Venetian homes having some sort of map by the late 1500s.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In medieval times, written directions of how to get somewhere were more common than the use of maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] With the Renaissance, cartography began to be seen as a metaphor for power.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Political leaders could lay claim to territories through the use of maps, and this was greatly aided by the religious and colonial expansion of Europe.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The Holy Land and other religious places were the most commonly mapped during the Renaissance.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the late 1400s to the late 1500s, Rome, Florence, and Venice dominated map-making and trade.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] It started in Florence in the mid-to late 1400s.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Map trade quickly shifted to Rome and Venice but then was overtaken by atlas makers in the late 16th century.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Map publishing in Venice was completed with humanities and book publishing in mind, rather than just informational use.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] There were two main printmaking technologies in the Renaissance: woodcut and copper-plate intaglio, referring to the medium used to transfer the image onto paper.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In woodcut, the map image is created as a relief chiseled from medium-grain hardwood.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The areas intended to be printed are inked and pressed against the sheet.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Being raised from the rest of the block, the map lines cause indentations in the paper that can often be felt on the back of the map.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] There are advantages to using relief to make maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] For one, a printmaker doesn't need a press because the maps could be developed as rubbings.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Woodblock is durable enough to be used many times before defects appear.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Existing printing presses can be used to create the prints rather than having to create a new one.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] On the other hand, it is hard to achieve fine detail with the relief technique.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Inconsistencies in linework are more apparent in woodcut than in intaglio.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] To improve quality in the late fifteenth century, a style of relief craftsmanship developed using fine chisels to carve the wood, rather than the more commonly used knife.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In intaglio, lines are engraved into workable metals, typically copper but sometimes brass.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The engraver spreads a thin sheet of wax over the metal plate and uses ink to draw the details.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Then, the engraver traces the lines with a stylus to etch them into the plate beneath.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The engraver can also use styli to prick holes along the drawn lines, trace along them with colored chalk, and then engrave the map.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Lines going in the same direction are carved at the same time, and then the plate is turned to carve lines going in a different direction.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] To print from the finished plate, ink is spread over the metal surface and scraped off such that it remains only in the etched channels.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Then the plate is pressed forcibly against the paper so that the ink in the channels is transferred to the paper.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The pressing is so forceful that it leaves a "plate mark" around the border of the map at the edge of the plate, within which the paper is depressed compared to the margins.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Copper and other metals were expensive at the time, so the plate was often reused for new maps or melted down for other purposes.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Whether woodcut or intaglio, the printed map is hung out to dry.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Once dry, it is usually placed in another press to flatten the paper.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Any type of paper that was available at the time could be used to print the map, but thicker paper was more durable.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Both relief and intaglio were used about equally by the end of the fifteenth century.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Lettering in mapmaking is important for denoting information.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Fine lettering is difficult in woodcut, where it often turned out square and blocky, contrary to the stylized, rounded writing style popular in Italy at the time.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] To improve quality, mapmakers developed fine chisels to carve the relief.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Intaglio lettering did not suffer the troubles of a coarse medium and so was able to express the looping cursive that came to be known as cancellaresca.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] There were custom-made reverse punches that were also used in metal engraving alongside freehand lettering.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The first use of color in map-making cannot be narrowed down to one reason.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] There are arguments that color started as a way to indicate information on the map, with aesthetics coming second.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] There are also arguments that color was first used on maps for aesthetics but then evolved into conveying information.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Either way, many maps of the Renaissance left the publisher without being colored, a practice that continued all the way into the 1800s.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] However, most publishers accepted orders from their patrons to have their maps or atlases colored if they wished.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Because all coloring was done by hand, the patron could request simple, cheap color, or more expensive, elaborate color, even going so far as silver or gold gilding.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The simplest coloring was merely outlines, such as of borders and along rivers.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Wash color meant painting regions with inks or watercolors.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Limning meant adding silver and gold leaf to the map to illuminate lettering, heraldic arms, or other decorative elements.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The early modern period saw the convergence of cartographical techniques across Eurasia and the exchange of mercantile mapping techniques via the Indian Ocean.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the early seventeenth century, the Selden map was created by a Chinese cartographer.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Historians have put its date of creation around 1620, but there is debate in this regard.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] This map's significance draws from historical misconceptions of East Asian cartography, the main one being that East Asians did not do cartography until Europeans arrived.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The map's depiction of trading routes, a compass rose, and scale bar points to the culmination of many map-making techniques incorporated into Chinese mercantile cartography.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In 1689, representatives of the Russian tsar and Qing Dynasty met near the border town of Nerchinsk, which was near the disputed border of the two powers, in eastern Siberia.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The two parties, with the Qing negotiation party bringing Jesuits as intermediaries, managed to work a treaty which placed the Amur River as the border between the Eurasian powers, and opened up trading relations between the two.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] This treaty's significance draws from the interaction between the two sides, and the intermediaries who were drawn from a wide variety of nationalities.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Maps of the Enlightenment period practically universally used copper plate intaglio, having abandoned the fragile, coarse woodcut technology.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Use of map projections evolved, with the double hemisphere being very common and Mercator's prestigious navigational projection gradually making more appearances.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Due to the paucity of information and the immense difficulty of surveying during the period, mapmakers frequently plagiarized material without giving credit to the original cartographer.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] For example, a famous map of North America known as the "Beaver Map" was published in 1715 by Herman Moll.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] This map is a close reproduction of a 1698 work by Nicolas de Fer.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] De Fer, in turn, had copied images that were first printed in books by Louis Hennepin, published in 1697, and François Du Creux, in 1664.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] By the late 18th century, mapmakers often credited the original publisher with something along the lines of, "After [the original cartographer]" in the map's title or cartouche.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In cartography, technology has continually changed in order to meet the demands of new generations of mapmakers and map users.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The first maps were produced manually, with brushes and parchment; so they varied in quality and were limited in distribution.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The advent of magnetic devices, such as the compass and much later, magnetic storage devices, allowed for the creation of far more accurate maps and the ability to store and manipulate them digitally.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Advances in mechanical devices such as the printing press, quadrant, and vernier allowed the mass production of maps and the creation of accurate reproductions from more accurate data.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Hartmann Schedel was one of the first cartographers to use the printing press to make maps more widely available.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Optical technology, such as the telescope, sextant, and other devices that use telescopes, allowed accurate land surveys and allowed mapmakers and navigators to find their latitude by measuring angles to the North Star at night or the Sun at noon.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Advances in photochemical technology, such as the lithographic and photochemical processes, make possible maps with fine details, which do not distort in shape and which resist moisture and wear.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] This also eliminated the need for engraving, which further speeded up map production.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the 20th century, aerial photography, satellite imagery, and remote sensing provided efficient, precise methods for mapping physical features, such as coastlines, roads, buildings, watersheds, and topography.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The United States Geological Survey has devised multiple new map projections, notably the Space Oblique Mercator for interpreting satellite ground tracks for mapping the surface.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The use of satellites and space telescopes now allows researchers to map other planets and moons in outer space.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The ability to superimpose spatially located variables onto existing maps has created new uses for maps and new industries to explore and exploit these potentials.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] These advances brought more accuracy to geographical and location-based data and widened the range of applications for cartography, for example in the development of satnav devices.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Today most commercial-quality maps are made using software of three main types: CAD, GIS and specialized illustration software.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Spatial information can be stored in a database, from which it can be extracted on demand.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] These tools lead to increasingly dynamic, interactive maps that can be manipulated digitally.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] On the other hand, we can observe a reverse trend.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In contemporary times, there is a resurgence of interest in the most beautiful periods of cartography, with various maps being created using, for example, Renaissance-style aesthetics.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] We encounter imitators or continuators of Renaissance traditions that merge the realms of science and art.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Field-rugged computers, GPS, and laser rangefinders make it possible to create maps directly from measurements made on site.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] There are technical and cultural aspects to producing maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In this sense, maps can sometimes be said to be biased.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The study of bias, influence, and agenda in making a map is what comprise a map's deconstruction.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] A central tenet of deconstructionism is that maps have power.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Other assertions are that maps are inherently biased and that we search for metaphor and rhetoric in maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] It is claimed that the Europeans promoted an "epistemological" understanding of the map as early as the 17th century.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] An example of this understanding is that "[European reproduction of terrain on maps] reality can be expressed in mathematical terms; that systematic observation and measurement offer the only route to cartographic truth…".
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] A common belief is that science heads in a direction of progress, and thus leads to more accurate representations of maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In this belief, European maps must be superior to others, which necessarily employed different map-making skills.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] "There was a 'not cartography' land where lurked an army of inaccurate, heretical, subjective, valuative, and ideologically distorted images.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Depictions of Africa are a common target of deconstructionism.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] According to deconstructionist models, cartography was used for strategic purposes associated with imperialism and as instruments and representations of power during the conquest of Africa.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The depiction of Africa and the low latitudes in general on the Mercator projection has been interpreted as imperialistic and as symbolic of subjugation due to the diminished proportions of those regions compared to higher latitudes where the European powers were concentrated.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Maps furthered imperialism and colonization of Africa in practical ways by showing basic information like roads, terrain, natural resources, settlements, and communities.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Through this, maps made European commerce in Africa possible by showing potential commercial routes and made natural resource extraction possible by depicting locations of resources.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Such maps also enabled military conquests and made them more efficient, and imperial nations further used them to put their conquests on display.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] These same maps were then used to cement territorial claims, such as at the Berlin Conference of 1884–1885.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Before 1749, maps of the African continent had African kingdoms drawn with assumed or contrived boundaries, with unknown or unexplored areas having drawings of animals, imaginary physical geographic features, and descriptive texts.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] B. d'Anville created the first map of the African continent that had blank spaces to represent the unknown territory.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In understanding basic maps, the field of cartography can be divided into two general categories: general cartography and thematic cartography.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] General cartography involves those maps that are constructed for a general audience and thus contain a variety of features.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] General maps exhibit many reference and location systems and often are produced in a series.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] For example, the 1:24,000 scale topographic maps of the United States Geological Survey (USGS) are a standard as compared to the 1:50,000 scale Canadian maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The government of the UK produces the classic 1:50,000 (replacing the older 1 inch to 1 mile) "Ordnance Survey" maps of the entire UK and with a range of correlated larger- and smaller-scale maps of great detail.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Many private mapping companies have also produced thematic map series.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Thematic cartography involves maps of specific geographic themes, oriented toward specific audiences.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] A couple of examples might be a dot map showing corn production in Indiana or a shaded area map of Ohio counties, divided into numerical choropleth classes.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] As the volume of geographic data has exploded over the last century, thematic cartography has become increasingly useful and necessary to interpret spatial, cultural and social data.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] A third type of map is known as an "orienteering," or special purpose map.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] This type of map falls somewhere between thematic and general maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] They combine general map elements with thematic attributes in order to design a map with a specific audience in mind.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Oftentimes, the type of audience an orienteering map is made for is in a particular industry or occupation.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] An example of this kind of map would be a municipal utility map.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] A topographic map is primarily concerned with the topographic description of a place, including (especially in the 20th and 21st centuries) the use of contour lines showing elevation.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Terrain or relief can be shown in a variety of ways (see Cartographic relief depiction).
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In the present era, one of the most widespread and advanced methods used to form topographic maps is to use computer software to generate digital elevation models which show shaded relief.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Before such software existed, cartographers had to draw shaded relief by hand.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] One cartographer who is respected as a master of hand-drawn shaded relief is the Swiss professor Eduard Imhof whose efforts in hill shading were so influential that his method became used around the world despite it being so labor-intensive.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] A topological map is a very general type of map, the kind one might sketch on a napkin.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] It often disregards scale and detail in the interest of clarity of communicating specific route or relational information.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Beck's London Underground map is an iconic example.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Although the most widely used map of "The Tube," it preserves little of reality: it varies scale constantly and abruptly, it straightens curved tracks, and it contorts directions.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The only topography on it is the River Thames, letting the reader know whether a station is north or south of the river.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] That and the topology of station order and interchanges between train lines are all that is left of the geographic space.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Yet those are all a typical passenger wishes to know, so the map fulfills its purpose.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Modern technology, including advances in printing, the advent of geographic information systems and graphics software, and the Internet, has vastly simplified the process of map creation and increased the palette of design options available to cartographers.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] This has led to a decreased focus on production skill, and an increased focus on quality design, the attempt to craft maps that are both aesthetically pleasing and practically useful for their intended purposes.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Its purpose may be as broad as teaching the major physical and political features of the entire world, or as narrow as convincing a neighbor to move a fence.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The audience may be as broad as the general public or as narrow as a single person.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Mapmakers use design principles to guide them in constructing a map that is effective for its purpose and audience.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The cartographic process spans many stages, starting from conceiving the need for a map and extending all the way through its consumption by an audience.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Conception begins with a real or imagined environment.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] As the cartographer gathers information about the subject, they consider how that information is structured and how that structure should inform the map's design.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Next, the cartographers experiment with generalization, symbolization, typography, and other map elements to find ways to portray the information so that the map reader can interpret the map as intended.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Guided by these experiments, the cartographer settles on a design and creates the map, whether in physical or electronic form.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Once finished, the map is delivered to its audience.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The map reader interprets the symbols and patterns on the map to draw conclusions and perhaps to take action.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] By the spatial perspectives they provide, maps help shape how we view the world.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Designing a map involves bringing together a number of elements and making a large number of decisions.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The elements of design fall into several broad topics, each of which has its own theory, its own research agenda, and its own best practices.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] That said, there are synergistic effects between these elements, meaning that the overall design process is not just working on each element one at a time, but an iterative feedback process of adjusting each to achieve the desired gestalt.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Some maps contain deliberate errors or distortions, either as propaganda or as a "watermark" to help the copyright owner identify infringement if the error appears in competitors' maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The latter often come in the form of nonexistent, misnamed, or misspelled "trap streets".
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Other names and forms for this are paper towns, fictitious entries, and copyright easter eggs.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Another motive for deliberate errors is cartographic "vandalism": a mapmaker wishing to leave their mark on the work.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Mount Richard, for example, was a fictitious peak on the Rocky Mountains' continental divide that appeared on a Boulder County, Colorado map in the early 1970s.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] It is believed to be the work of draftsman Richard Ciacci.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] The fiction was not discovered until two years later.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] In Switzerland's official maps, mapmakers have hidden illustrations of a hiker, fish, marmot, and more for over a century.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] Sandy Island in New Caledonia is an example of a fictitious location that stubbornly survives, reappearing on new maps copied from older maps while being deleted from other new editions.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] With the emergence of the internet and Web mapping, technologies allow for the creation and distribution of maps by people without proper cartographic training are readily available.
[src:geospatial-gis/cartography] This has led to maps that ignore cartographic conventions and are potentially misleading.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-data-and-information] Geographic data and information is stored in geographic databases and geographic information systems (GIS).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-data-and-information] There are many different formats of geodata, including vector files, raster files, web files, and multi-temporal data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A **geographic information system** (**GIS**) consists of integrated computer hardware and software that store, manage, analyze, edit, output, and visualize geographic data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Much of this often happens within a spatial database; however, this is not essential to meet the definition of a GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In a broader sense, one may consider such a system also to include human users and support staff, procedures and workflows, the body of knowledge of relevant concepts and methods, and institutional organizations.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The uncounted plural, *geographic information systems*, also abbreviated GIS, is the most common term for the industry and profession concerned with these systems.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The academic discipline that studies these systems and their underlying geographic principles, may also be abbreviated as GIS, but the unambiguous GIScience is more common.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIScience is often considered a subdiscipline of geography within the branch of technical geography.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Geographic information systems are used in multiple technologies, processes, techniques and methods.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] They are attached to various operations and numerous applications, that relate to: engineering, planning, management, transport/logistics, insurance, telecommunications, and business, as well as the natural sciences such as forestry, ecology, and Earth science.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For this reason, GIS and location intelligence applications are at the foundation of location-enabled services, which rely on geographic analysis and visualization.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS provides the ability to relate previously unrelated information, through the use of location as the "key index variable".
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Locations and extents that are found in the Earth's spacetime are able to be recorded through the date and time of occurrence, along with x, y, and z coordinates; representing, longitude (*x*), latitude (*y*), and elevation (*z*).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] All Earth-based, spatial–temporal, location and extent references should be relatable to one another, and ultimately, to a "real" physical location or extent.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This key characteristic of GIS has begun to open new avenues of scientific inquiry and studies.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] While digital GIS dates to the mid-1960s, when Roger Tomlinson first coined the phrase "geographic information system", many of the geographic concepts and methods that GIS automates date back decades earlier.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] One of the first known instances in which spatial analysis was used came from the field of epidemiology in the *Rapport sur la marche et les effets du choléra dans Paris et le département de la Seine* (1832).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] French cartographer and geographer Charles Picquet created a map outlining the forty-eight districts in Paris, using halftone color gradients, to provide a visual representation for the number of reported deaths due to cholera per every 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In 1854, John Snow, an epidemiologist and physician, was able to determine the source of a cholera outbreak in London through the use of spatial analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Snow achieved this through plotting the residence of each casualty on a map of the area, as well as the nearby water sources.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Once these points were marked, he was able to identify the water source within the cluster that was responsible for the outbreak.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This was one of the earliest successful uses of a geographic methodology in pinpointing the source of an outbreak in epidemiology.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] While the basic elements of topography and theme existed previously in cartography, Snow's map was unique due to his use of cartographic methods, not only to depict, but also to analyze clusters of geographically dependent phenomena.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The early 20th century saw the development of photozincography, which allowed maps to be split into layers, for example one layer for vegetation and another for water.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This was particularly used for printing contours – drawing these was a labour-intensive task but having them on a separate layer meant they could be worked on without the other layers to confuse the draughtsman.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This work was initially drawn on glass plates, but later plastic film was introduced, with the advantages of being lighter, using less storage space and being less brittle, among others.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] When all the layers were finished, they were combined into one image using a large process camera.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Once color printing came in, the layers idea was also used for creating separate printing plates for each color.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] While the use of layers much later became one of the typical features of a contemporary GIS, the photographic process just described is not considered a GIS in itself – as the maps were just images with no database to link them to.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Two additional developments are notable in the early days of GIS: Ian McHarg's publication *Design with Nature* and its map overlay method and the introduction of a street network into the U.S.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Census Bureau's DIME (Dual Independent Map Encoding) system.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The first publication detailing the use of computers to facilitate cartography was written by Waldo Tobler in 1959.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Further computer hardware development spurred by nuclear weapon research led to more widespread general-purpose computer "mapping" applications by the early 1960s.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In 1963, the world's first true operational GIS was developed in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada, by the federal Department of Forestry and Rural Development.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A rating classification factor was also added to permit analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] CGIS was an improvement over "computer mapping" applications as it provided capabilities for data storage, overlay, measurement, and digitizing/scanning.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] It supported a national coordinate system that spanned the continent, coded lines as arcs having a true embedded topology and it stored the attribute and locational information in separate files.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] As a result of this, Tomlinson has become known as the "father of GIS", particularly for his use of overlays in promoting the spatial analysis of convergent geographic data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] CGIS lasted into the 1990s and built a large digital land resource database in Canada.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] It was developed as a mainframe-based system in support of federal and provincial resource planning and management.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Its strength was continent-wide analysis of complex datasets.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The CGIS was never available commercially.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These programs were the first examples of general-purpose GIS software that was not developed for a particular installation, and was very influential on future commercial software, such as Esri ARC/INFO, released in 1983.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Working in the Harvard Lab, Tom Waugh developed his vector-based Geographic Information Mapping and Manipulation System (GIMMS) software from 1969.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] He returned to the University of Edinburgh and this software was sold commercially from 1973.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] By 1977 it was used at 300 sites worldwide.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This can be considered the first globally used GIS which anticipated some key characteristics of the Harvard Odyssey system by nearly five years and ARC/INFO by a decade.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In 1986, Mapping Display and Analysis System (MIDAS), the first desktop GIS product, was released for MS-DOS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] It was renamed in 1990 to MapInfo for Windows when it was ported to Windows.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This began the process of moving GIS from the research department into the business environment.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] By the end of the 20th century, the rapid growth in various systems had been consolidated and standardized on relatively few platforms and users were beginning to explore viewing GIS data over the Internet, requiring data format and transfer standards.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] More recently, a growing number of free, open-source GIS packages run on a range of operating systems and can be customized to perform specific tasks.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The major trend of the 21st century has been the integration of GIS capabilities with other Information technology and Internet infrastructure, such as relational databases, cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS), and mobile computing.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Starting in the late 1970s, many software packages have been created specifically for GIS applications.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Esri's ArcGIS, which includes ArcGIS Pro and the legacy software ArcMap, currently dominates the GIS market.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Other examples of GIS include Autodesk and MapInfo Professional and open-source programs such as QGIS, GRASS GIS, MapGuide, and Hadoop-GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These and other desktop GIS applications include a full suite of capabilities for entering, managing, analyzing, and visualizing geographic data, and are designed to be used on their own.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Starting in the late 1990s with the emergence of the Internet, as computer network technology progressed, GIS infrastructure and data began to move to servers, providing another mechanism for providing GIS capabilities.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This was facilitated by standalone software installed on a server, similar to other server software such as HTTP servers and relational database management systems, enabling clients to have access to GIS data and processing tools without having to install specialized desktop software.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These networks are known as distributed GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This strategy has been extended through the Internet and development of cloud-based GIS platforms such as ArcGIS Online and GIS-specialized software as a service (SAAS).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The use of the Internet to facilitate distributed GIS is known as Internet GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] An alternative approach is the integration of some or all of these capabilities into other software or information technology architectures.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] One example is a spatial extension to Object-relational database software, which defines a geometry datatype so that spatial data can be stored in relational tables, and extensions to SQL for spatial analysis operations such as overlay.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The core of any GIS is a database that contains representations of geographic phenomena, modeling their *geometry* (location and shape) and their *properties* or *attributes*.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A GIS database may be stored in a variety of forms, such as a collection of separate data files or a single spatially-enabled relational database.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Collecting and managing these data usually constitutes the bulk of the time and financial resources of a project, far more than other aspects such as analysis and mapping.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS uses spatio-temporal (space-time) location as the key index variable for all other information.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Just as a relational database containing text or numbers can relate many different tables using common key index variables, GIS can relate otherwise unrelated information by using location as the key index variable.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The key is the location and/or extent in space-time.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Any variable that can be located spatially, and increasingly also temporally, can be referenced using a GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Locations or extents in Earth space–time may be recorded as dates/times of occurrence, and x, y, and z coordinates representing, longitude, latitude, and elevation, respectively.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These GIS coordinates may represent other quantified systems of temporo-spatial reference (for example, film frame number, stream gage station, highway mile-marker, surveyor benchmark, building address, street intersection, entrance gate, water depth sounding, POS or CAD drawing origin/units).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Related by accurate spatial information, an incredible variety of real-world and projected past or future data can be analyzed, interpreted and represented.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This key characteristic of GIS has begun to open new avenues of scientific inquiry into behaviors and patterns of real-world information that previously had not been systematically correlated.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS data represents phenomena that exist in the real world, such as roads, land use, elevation, trees, waterways, and states.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The most common types of phenomena that are represented in data can be divided into two conceptualizations: discrete objects (e.g., a house, a road) and continuous fields (e.g., rainfall amount or population density).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Other types of geographic phenomena, such as events (e.g., location of World War II battles), processes (e.g., extent of suburbanization), and masses (e.g., types of soil in an area) are represented less commonly or indirectly, or are modeled in analysis procedures rather than data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Traditionally, there are two broad methods used to store data in a GIS for both kinds of abstractions mapping references: raster images and vector.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Points, lines, and polygons represent vector data of mapped location attribute references.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A new hybrid method of storing data is that of identifying point clouds, which combine three-dimensional points with RGB information at each point, returning a 3D color image.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS thematic maps then are becoming more and more realistically visually descriptive of what they set out to show or determine.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] All of these methods can consume significant time, finances, and other resources.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Survey data can be directly entered into a GIS from digital data collection systems on survey instruments using a technique called coordinate geometry (COGO).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Positions from a global navigation satellite system (GNSS) like the Global Positioning System can also be collected and then imported into a GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A current trend in data collection gives users the ability to use field computers with the ability to edit live data using wireless connections or disconnected editing sessions.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The current trend is to use applications available on smartphones and PDAs in the form of mobile GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This has been enhanced by the availability of low-cost mapping-grade GPS units with decimeter accuracy in real time.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This eliminates the need to post process, import, and update the data in the office after fieldwork has been collected.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This includes the ability to incorporate positions collected using a laser rangefinder.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] New technologies also allow users to create maps as well as analysis directly in the field, making projects more efficient and mapping more accurate.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Remotely sensed data also plays an important role in data collection and consist of sensors attached to a platform.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Sensors include cameras, digital scanners and lidar, while platforms usually consist of aircraft and satellites.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In England in the mid-1990s, hybrid kite/balloons called helikites first pioneered the use of compact airborne digital cameras as airborne geo-information systems.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Aircraft measurement software, accurate to 0.4 mm, was used to link the photographs and measure the ground.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Helikites are inexpensive and gather more accurate data than aircraft.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Helikites can be used over roads, railways and towns where unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) are banned.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Recently, aerial data collection has become more accessible with miniature UAVs and drones.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, the Aeryon Scout was used to map a 50-acre area with a ground sample distance of 1 inch (2.54 cm) in only 12 minutes.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The majority of digital data currently comes from photo interpretation of aerial photographs.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Soft-copy workstations are used to digitize features directly from stereo pairs of digital photographs.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These systems allow data to be captured in two and three dimensions, with elevations measured directly from a stereo pair using principles of photogrammetry.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Analog aerial photos must be scanned before being entered into a soft-copy system, for high-quality digital cameras this step is skipped.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Satellite remote sensing provides another important source of spatial data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Here satellites use different sensor packages to passively measure the reflectance from parts of the electromagnetic spectrum or radio waves that were sent out from an active sensor such as radar.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Remote sensing collects raster data that can be further processed using different bands to identify objects and classes of interest, such as land cover.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The most common method of data creation is digitization, where a hard copy map or survey plan is transferred into a digital medium through the use of a CAD program, and geo-referencing capabilities.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] With the wide availability of ortho-rectified imagery (from satellites, aircraft, Helikites and UAVs), heads-up digitizing is becoming the main avenue through which geographic data is extracted.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Heads-up digitizing involves the tracing of geographic data directly on top of the aerial imagery instead of by the traditional method of tracing the geographic form on a separate digitizing tablet (heads-down digitizing).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Heads-down digitizing, or manual digitizing, uses a special magnetic pen, or stylus, that feeds information into a computer to create an identical, digital map.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Some tablets use a mouse-like tool, called a puck, instead of a stylus.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The puck has a small window with cross-hairs which allows for greater precision and pinpointing map features.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Though heads-up digitizing is more commonly used, heads-down digitizing is still useful for digitizing maps of poor quality.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Existing data printed on paper or PET film maps can be digitized or scanned to produce digital data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A digitizer produces vector data as an operator traces points, lines, and polygon boundaries from a map.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Scanning a map results in raster data that could be further processed to produce vector data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] When data is captured, the user should consider if the data should be captured with either a relative accuracy or absolute accuracy, since this could not only influence how information will be interpreted but also the cost of data capture.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] After entering data into a GIS, the data usually requires editing, to remove errors, or further processing.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For vector data it must be made "topologically correct" before it can be used for some advanced analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, in a road network, lines must connect with nodes at an intersection.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Errors such as undershoots and overshoots must also be removed.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For scanned maps, blemishes on the source map may need to be removed from the resulting raster.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, a fleck of dirt might connect two lines that should not be connected.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The earth can be represented by various models, each of which may provide a different set of coordinates (e.g., latitude, longitude, elevation) for any given point on the Earth's surface.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The simplest model is to assume the earth is a perfect sphere.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] As more measurements of the earth have accumulated, the models of the earth have become more sophisticated and more accurate.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In fact, there are models called datums that apply to different areas of the earth to provide increased accuracy, like North American Datum of 1983 for U.S. measurements, and the World Geodetic System for worldwide measurements.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The latitude and longitude on a map made against a local datum may not be the same as one obtained from a GPS receiver.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Converting coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In popular GIS software, data projected in latitude/longitude is often represented as a Geographic coordinate system.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, data in latitude/longitude if the datum is the 'North American Datum of 1983' is denoted by 'GCS North American 1983'.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] While no digital model can be a perfect representation of the real world, it is important that GIS data be of a high quality.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In keeping with the principle of homomorphism, the data must be close enough to reality so that the results of GIS procedures correctly correspond to the results of real world processes.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This means that there is no single standard for data quality, because the necessary degree of quality depends on the scale and purpose of the tasks for which it is to be used.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] is the amount of difference between them.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] on 1 April 2020 was 2,304,580; if it was actually 2,310,674, this would be an error and thus a lack of attribute accuracy.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The degree of refinement in a represented value.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In a quantitative property, this is the number of significant digits in the measured value.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] An imprecise value is vague or ambiguous, including a range of possible values.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, if one were to say that the population of Houston on 1 April 2020 was "about 2.3 million," this statement would be imprecise, but likely accurate because the correct value (and many incorrect values) are included.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] As with accuracy, representations of location, property, and time can all be more or less precise.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] is closely related to precision in maps, as it dictates a desirable level of spatial precision, but is problematic in GIS, where a data set can be shown at a variety of display scales (including scales that would not be appropriate for the quality of the data).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A general acknowledgement of the presence of error and imprecision in geographic data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This is sometimes used as a collective term for all or most aspects of data quality.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The degree to which an aspect (location, property, or time) of a phenomenon is inherently imprecise, rather than the imprecision being in a measured value.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] are commonly used to manage vagueness in geographic data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The degree to which a data set represents all of the actual features that it purports to include.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] " is missing some actual streets, it is incomplete.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The most recent point in time at which a data set claims to be an accurate representation of reality.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This is a concern for the majority of GIS applications, which attempt to represent the world "at present," in which case older data is of lower quality.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The degree to which the representations of the many phenomena in a data set correctly correspond with each other.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] between spatial objects is an especially important aspect of consistency.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] tools such as shortest path would still give correct results.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] methods and other processing tools derives from the quality of input data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] is a common operation used in many ways in GIS; because it generates estimates of values between known measurements, the results will always be more precise, but less certain (as each estimate has an unknown amount of error).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The quality of a dataset is very dependent upon its sources, and the methods used to create it.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Land surveyors have been able to provide a high level of positional accuracy using high-end GPS equipment, but GPS locations on the average smartphone are much less accurate.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Common datasets such as digital terrain and aerial imagery are available in a wide variety of levels of quality, especially spatial precision.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Paper maps, which have been digitized for many years as a data source, can also be of widely varying quality.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A quantitative analysis of maps brings accuracy issues into focus.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The electronic and other equipment used to make measurements for GIS is far more precise than the machines of conventional map analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] All geographical data are inherently inaccurate, and these inaccuracies will propagate through GIS operations in ways that are difficult to predict.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Data restructuring can be performed by a GIS to convert data into different formats.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, a GIS may be used to convert a satellite image map to a vector structure by generating lines around all cells with the same classification, while determining the cell spatial relationships, such as adjacency or inclusion.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] More advanced data processing can occur with image processing, a technique developed in the late 1960s by NASA and the private sector to provide contrast enhancement, false color rendering and a variety of other techniques including use of two dimensional Fourier transforms.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Since digital data is collected and stored in various ways, the two data sources may not be entirely compatible.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] So a GIS must be able to convert geographic data from one structure to another.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In so doing, the implicit assumptions behind different ontologies and classifications require analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Object ontologies have gained increasing prominence as a consequence of object-oriented programming and sustained work by Barry Smith and co-workers.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Spatial ETL tools provide the data processing functionality of traditional extract, transform, load (ETL) software, but with a primary focus on the ability to manage spatial data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] They provide GIS users with the ability to translate data between different standards and proprietary formats, whilst geometrically transforming the data en route.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These tools can come in the form of add-ins to existing wider-purpose software such as spreadsheets.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS spatial analysis is a rapidly changing field, and GIS packages are increasingly including analytical tools as standard built-in facilities, as optional toolsets, as add-ins or 'analysts'.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In many instances these are provided by the original software suppliers (commercial vendors or collaborative non-commercial development teams), while in other cases facilities have been developed and are provided by third parties.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Furthermore, many products offer software development kits (SDKs), programming languages and language support, scripting facilities and/or special interfaces for developing one's own analytical tools or variants.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The increased availability has created a new dimension to business intelligence termed "spatial intelligence" which, when openly delivered via intranet, democratizes access to geographic and social network data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Geospatial intelligence, based on GIS spatial analysis, has also become a key element for security.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS as a whole can be described as conversion to a vectorial representation or to any other digitisation process.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Many geographic tasks involve the terrain, the shape of the surface of the earth, such as hydrology, earthworks, and biogeography.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Thus, terrain data is often a core dataset in a GIS, usually in the form of a raster Digital elevation model (DEM) or a Triangulated irregular network (TIN).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A variety of tools are available in most GIS software for analyzing terrain, often by creating derivative datasets that represent a specific aspect of the surface.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Most of these are generated using algorithms that are discrete simplifications of vector calculus.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Slope, aspect, and surface curvature in terrain analysis are all derived from neighborhood operations using elevation values of a cell's adjacent neighbours.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Each of these is strongly affected by the level of detail in the terrain data, such as the resolution of a DEM, which should be chosen carefully.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Distance is a key part of solving many geographic tasks, usually due to the friction of distance.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Thus, a wide variety of analysis tools have analyze distance in some form, such as buffers, Voronoi or Thiessen polygons, Cost distance analysis, and network analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] It is difficult to relate wetlands maps to rainfall amounts recorded at different points such as airports, television stations, and schools.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A GIS, however, can be used to depict two- and three-dimensional characteristics of the Earth's surface, subsurface, and atmosphere from information points.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, a GIS can quickly generate a map with isopleth or contour lines that indicate differing amounts of rainfall.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Such a map can be thought of as a rainfall contour map.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Many sophisticated methods can estimate the characteristics of surfaces from a limited number of point measurements.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A two-dimensional contour map created from the surface modeling of rainfall point measurements may be overlaid and analyzed with any other map in a GIS covering the same area.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This GIS derived map can then provide additional information – such as the viability of water power potential as a renewable energy source.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Similarly, GIS can be used to compare other renewable energy resources to find the best geographic potential for a region.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Additionally, from a series of three-dimensional points, or digital elevation model, isopleth lines representing elevation contours can be generated, along with slope analysis, shaded relief, and other elevation products.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Watersheds can be easily defined for any given reach, by computing all of the areas contiguous and uphill from any given point of interest.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Similarly, an expected thalweg of where surface water would want to travel in intermittent and permanent streams can be computed from elevation data in the GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A GIS can recognize and analyze the spatial relationships that exist within digitally stored spatial data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These topological relationships allow complex spatial modelling and analysis to be performed.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Topological relationships between geometric entities traditionally include adjacency (what adjoins what), containment (what encloses what), and proximity (how close something is to something else).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Geometric networks are linear networks of objects that can be used to represent interconnected features, and to perform special spatial analysis on them.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A geometric network is composed of edges, which are connected at junction points, similar to graphs in mathematics and computer science.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Just like graphs, networks can have weight and flow assigned to its edges, which can be used to represent various interconnected features more accurately.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Geometric networks are often used to model road networks and public utility networks, such as electric, gas, and water networks.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Network modeling is also commonly employed in transportation planning, hydrology modeling, and infrastructure modeling.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Dana Tomlin coined the term *cartographic modeling* in his PhD dissertation (1983); he later used it in the title of his book, *Geographic Information Systems and Cartographic Modeling* (1990).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Cartographic modeling refers to a process where several thematic layers of the same area are produced, processed, and analyzed.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Tomlin used raster layers, but the overlay method (see below) can be used more generally.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Operations on map layers can be combined into algorithms, and eventually into simulation or optimization models.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The combination of several spatial datasets (points, lines, or polygons) creates a new output vector dataset, visually similar to stacking several maps of the same region.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These overlays are similar to mathematical Venn diagram overlays.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A union overlay combines the geographic features and attribute tables of both inputs into a single new output.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] An intersect overlay defines the area where both inputs overlap and retains a set of attribute fields for each.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A symmetric difference overlay defines an output area that includes the total area of both inputs except for the overlapping area.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Data extraction is a GIS process similar to vector overlay, though it can be used in either vector or raster data analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Rather than combining the properties and features of both datasets, data extraction involves using a "clip" or "mask" to extract the features of one data set that fall within the spatial extent of another dataset.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In raster data analysis, the overlay of datasets is accomplished through a process known as "local operation on multiple rasters" or "map algebra", through a function that combines the values of each raster's matrix.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This function may weigh some inputs more than others through use of an "index model" that reflects the influence of various factors upon a geographic phenomenon.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Geostatistics is a branch of statistics that deals with field data, spatial data with a continuous index.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] It provides methods to model spatial correlation, and predict values at arbitrary locations (interpolation).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] When phenomena are measured, the observation methods dictate the accuracy of any subsequent analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Due to the nature of the data (e.g. traffic patterns in an urban environment; weather patterns over the Pacific Ocean), a constant or dynamic degree of precision is always lost in the measurement.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This loss of precision is determined from the scale and distribution of the data collection.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] To determine the statistical relevance of the analysis, an average is determined so that points (gradients) outside of any immediate measurement can be included to determine their predicted behavior.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This is due to the limitations of the applied statistic and data collection methods, and interpolation is required to predict the behavior of particles, points, and locations that are not directly measurable.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Interpolation is the process by which a surface is created, usually a raster dataset, through the input of data collected at a number of sample points.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] There are several forms of interpolation, each which treats the data differently, depending on the properties of the data set.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In comparing interpolation methods, the first consideration should be whether or not the source data will change (exact or approximate).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Next is whether the method is subjective, a human interpretation, or objective.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Then there is the nature of transitions between points: are they abrupt or gradual.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Finally, there is whether a method is global (it uses the entire data set to form the model), or local where an algorithm is repeated for a small section of terrain.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Interpolation is a justified measurement because of a spatial autocorrelation principle that recognizes that data collected at any position will have a great similarity to, or influence of those locations within its immediate vicinity.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Digital elevation models, triangulated irregular networks, edge-finding algorithms, Thiessen polygons, Fourier analysis, (weighted) moving averages, inverse distance weighting, kriging, spline, and trend surface analysis are all mathematical methods to produce interpolative data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Geocoding is interpolating spatial locations (X,Y coordinates) from street addresses or any other spatially referenced data such as ZIP Codes, parcel lots and address locations.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A reference theme is required to geocode individual addresses, such as a road centerline file with address ranges.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The individual address locations have historically been interpolated, or estimated, by examining address ranges along a road segment.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These are usually provided in the form of a table or database.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The software will then place a dot approximately where that address belongs along the segment of centerline.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, an address point of 500 will be at the midpoint of a line segment that starts with address 1 and ends with address 1,000.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Geocoding can also be applied against actual parcel data, typically from municipal tax maps.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] In this case, the result of the geocoding will be an actually positioned space as opposed to an interpolated point.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This approach is being increasingly used to provide more precise location information.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Reverse geocoding is the process of returning an estimated street address number as it relates to a given coordinate.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, a user can click on a road centerline theme (thus providing a coordinate) and have information returned that reflects the estimated house number.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This house number is interpolated from a range assigned to that road segment.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] If the user clicks at the midpoint of a segment that starts with address 1 and ends with 100, the returned value will be somewhere near 50.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Note that reverse geocoding does not return actual addresses, only estimates of what should be there based on the predetermined range.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Coupled with GIS, multi-criteria decision analysis methods support decision-makers in analysing a set of alternative spatial solutions, such as the most likely ecological habitat for restoration, against multiple criteria, such as vegetation cover or roads.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] MCDA uses decision rules to aggregate the criteria, which allows the alternative solutions to be ranked or prioritised.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS MCDA may reduce costs and time involved in identifying potential restoration sites.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS or spatial data mining is the application of data mining methods to spatial data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Data mining, which is the partially automated search for hidden patterns in large databases, offers great potential benefits for applied GIS-based decision making.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Typical applications include environmental monitoring.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A characteristic of such applications is that spatial correlation between data measurements require the use of specialized algorithms for more efficient data analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] GIS-based spatial modeling has increasingly been combined with machine learning techniques to identify and forecast regional inequities in health and social outcomes, including healthcare access and insurance enrollment.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Cartography is the design and production of maps, or visual representations of spatial data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The vast majority of modern cartography is done with the help of computers, usually using GIS but production of quality cartography is also achieved by importing layers into a design program to refine it.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Most GIS software gives the user substantial control over the appearance of the data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] First, it produces graphics on the screen or on paper that convey the results of analysis to the people who make decisions about resources.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Wall maps and other graphics can be generated, allowing the viewer to visualize and thereby understand the results of analyses or simulations of potential events.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Web Map Servers facilitate distribution of generated maps through web browsers using various implementations of web-based application programming interfaces (AJAX, Java, Flash, etc.).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Second, other database information can be generated for further analysis or use.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] An example would be a list of all addresses within one mile (1.6 km) of a toxic spill.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] An archeochrome is a new way of displaying spatial data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] It is a thematic on a 3D map that is applied to a specific building or a part of a building.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] It is suited to the visual display of heat-loss data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Traditional maps are abstractions of the real world, a sampling of important elements portrayed on a sheet of paper with symbols to represent physical objects.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] People who use maps must interpret these symbols.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Topographic maps show the shape of land surface with contour lines or with shaded relief.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Today, graphic display techniques such as shading based on altitude in a GIS can make relationships among map elements visible, heightening one's ability to extract and analyze information.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, two types of data were combined in a GIS to produce a perspective view of a portion of San Mateo County, California.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] A GIS was used to register and combine the two images to render the three-dimensional perspective view looking down the San Andreas Fault, using the Thematic Mapper image pixels, but shaded using the elevation of the landforms.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] The GIS display depends on the viewing point of the observer and time of day of the display, to properly render the shadows created by the sun's rays at that latitude, longitude, and time of day.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] There has been a proliferation of free-to-use and easily accessible mapping software such as the proprietary web applications Google Maps and Bing Maps, as well as the free and open-source alternative OpenStreetMap.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These services give the public access to huge amounts of geographic data, perceived by many users to be as trustworthy and usable as professional information.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] For example, during the COVID-19 pandemic, web maps hosted on dashboards were used to rapidly disseminate case data to the general public.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Some of them, like Google Maps and OpenLayers, expose an application programming interface (API) that enable users to create custom applications.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These toolkits commonly offer street maps, aerial/satellite imagery, geocoding, searches, and routing functionality.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Web mapping has also uncovered the potential of crowdsourcing geodata in projects like OpenStreetMap, which is a collaborative project to create a free editable map of the world.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] These mashup projects have been proven to provide a high level of value and benefit to end users outside that possible through traditional geographic information.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] Web mapping allows for the creation and distribution of maps by people without proper cartographic training.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p01] This has led to maps that ignore cartographic conventions and are potentially misleading, with one study finding that more than half of United States state government COVID-19 dashboards did not follow these conventions.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Since its origin in the 1960s, GIS has been used in an ever-increasing range of applications, corroborating the widespread importance of location and aided by the continuing reduction in the barriers to adopting geospatial technology.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The implementation of a GIS is often driven by jurisdictional (such as a city), purpose, or application requirements.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Generally, a GIS implementation may be custom-designed for an organization.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Hence, a GIS deployment developed for an application, jurisdiction, enterprise, or purpose may not be necessarily interoperable or compatible with a GIS that has been developed for some other application, jurisdiction, enterprise, or purpose.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS is also used in digital marketing and SEO for audience segmentation based on location.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic Information Systems (GIS) has become an integral part of aquatic science and limnology.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Features associated with water are thus ever-changing.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] To be able to keep up with these changes, technological advancements have given scientists methods to enhance all aspects of scientific investigation, from satellite tracking of wildlife to computer mapping of habitats.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Agencies like the US Geological Survey, US Fish and Wildlife Service as well as other federal and state agencies are utilizing GIS to aid in their conservation efforts.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS has been applied to the long-term monitoring of shoreline change and coastal erosion, integrating historical aerial photography, satellite imagery and GPS surveys to quantify retreat rates and assess coastal vulnerability.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] A geographic information system (GIS) consists of integrated computer hardware and software that store, manage, analyze, edit, output, and visualize geographic data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Geospatial disaster response uses geospatial data and tools to help emergency responders, land managers, and scientists respond to disasters.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Geospatial data can help save lives, reduce damage, and improve communication.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] In the United States, FEMA's Response Geospatial Office is responsible for the agency's capture, analysis and development of GIS products to enhance situational awareness and enable expeditions and effective decision making.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The RGO's mission is to support decision makers in understanding the size, scope, and extent of disaster impacts so they can deliver resources to the communities most in need.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic information system (GIS) is a commonly used tool for environmental management, modelling and planning.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] As simply defined by Michael Goodchild, GIS is as "a computer system for handling geographic information in a digital form".
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] In recent years it has played an integral role in participatory, collaborative and open data philosophies.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Social and technological evolutions have elevated *digital* and *environmental* agendas to the forefront of public policy, the global media and the private sector.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS in environmental contamination is the use of GIS software to map and analyze contaminants on Earth, including soil contamination, water pollution, and air pollution.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Various GIS methods are used to conduct spatial analysis of pollutants to, identify, monitor, and assess them.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS can use other technologies to advance their process of analysis, including remote sensing, LIDAR, GeoAI, and WebGIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] One method includes spatial interpolation, which allows for a more efficient approach to remediation and monitoring of soil and water contaminants.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Contamination by metals and other contaminants has become a significant environmental problem after industrialization across many parts of the world.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] As a result, environmental agencies are placed in charge of remediating, monitoring, and mitigating the soil contamination sites.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS is used to monitor sites for metal contaminants on Earth to identify high-risk sites where remediation and monitoring are needed.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] A geological map or geologic map is a special-purpose map made to show various geological features.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Rock units or geologic strata are shown by color or symbols.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Bedding planes and structural features such as faults, folds, are shown with strike and dip or trend and plunge symbols which give three-dimensional orientations features.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Geological mapping is an interpretive process involving multiple types of information, from analytical data to personal observation, all synthesized and recorded by the geologist.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Geologic observations have traditionally been recorded on paper, whether on standardized note cards, in a notebook, or on a map.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] In geology, GIS is increasingly used for the assessment and forecasting of mineral deposits, particularly for commonly occurring mineral resources (COMR) such as construction sands, clays, and peat.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Unlike the dense and uniformly distributed borehole data typical of oil and gas exploration, COMR exploration often relies on sparse and unevenly distributed datasets.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] This requires specialized GIS algorithms, for instance, those based on Voronoi diagrams, to create three-dimensional geological models from incomplete information.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Beyond modeling, GIS enables a comprehensive evaluation by integrating geological and industrial parameters—such as overburden ratio and deposit thickness—with land-use data to classify and rank potential mining sites based on their economic and environmental acceptability.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] A case study of this integrated approach was demonstrated for the Brest region in Belarus, where a regional digital model was created to forecast and evaluate new non-metallic mineral deposits, considering both geological constraints and land-use regulations for open-pit mining development.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic information systems (GIS) play a constantly evolving role in geospatial intelligence (GEOINT) and United States national security.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] These technologies allow a user to efficiently manage, analyze, and produce geospatial data, to combine GEOINT with other forms of intelligence collection, and to perform highly developed analysis and visual production of geospatial data.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Therefore, GIS produces up-to-date and more reliable GEOINT to reduce uncertainty for a decisionmaker.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Since GIS programs are Web-enabled, a user can constantly work with a decision maker to solve their GEOINT and national security related problems from anywhere in the world.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] There are many types of GIS software used in GEOINT and national security, such as Google Earth, ERDAS IMAGINE, GeoNetwork opensource, and Esri ArcGIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] A historical geographic information system (also written as historical GIS or HGIS) is a geographic information system that may display, store and analyze data of past geographies and track changes in time.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The use of digital maps generated by GIS has also influenced the development of an academic field known as spatial humanities.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic information systems (GISs) have become a useful and important tool in the field of hydrology to study and manage Earth's water resources.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Climate change and greater demands on water resources require a more knowledgeable disposition of arguably one of our most vital resources.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Because water in its occurrence varies spatially and temporally throughout the hydrologic cycle, its study using GIS is especially practical.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Whereas previous GIS systems were mostly static in their geospatial representation of hydrologic features, GIS platforms are becoming increasingly dynamic, narrowing the gap between historical data and current hydrologic reality.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Participatory GIS (PGIS) or public participation geographic information system (PPGIS) is a participatory approach to spatial planning and spatial information and communications management.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Geographic information systems (GISs) and geographic information science (GIScience) combine computer-mapping capabilities with additional database management and data analysis tools.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Commercial GIS systems are very powerful and have touched many applications and industries, including environmental science, urban planning, agricultural applications, and others.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Traditional knowledge Geographic Information Systems (GIS) is a toolset of systems designed to document and utilize traditional knowledge from communities around the world.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Traditional knowledge GIS differ from ordinary cognitive maps in that they express environmental and spiritual relationships among real and conceptual entities.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] This toolset focuses on cultural preservation, land rights disputes, natural resource management, and economic development.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC) is an international industry consortium of 384 companies, government agencies, universities, and individuals participating in a consensus process to develop publicly available geoprocessing specifications.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Open Geospatial Consortium protocols include Web Map Service, and Web Feature Service.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS products are broken down by the OGC into two categories, based on how completely and accurately the software follows the OGC specifications.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The condition of the Earth's surface, atmosphere, and subsurface can be examined by feeding satellite data into a GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS technology gives researchers the ability to examine the variations in Earth processes over days, months, and years through the use of cartographic visualizations.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] As an example, the changes in vegetation vigor through a growing season can be animated to determine when drought was most extensive in a particular region.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The resulting graphic represents a rough measure of plant health.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Working with two variables over time would then allow researchers to detect regional differences in the lag between a decline in rainfall and its effect on vegetation.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS technology and the availability of digital data on regional and global scales enable such analyses.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The satellite sensor output used to generate a vegetation graphic is produced for example by the advanced very-high-resolution radiometer (AVHRR).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] This sensor system detects the amounts of energy reflected from the Earth's surface across various bands of the spectrum for surface areas of about 1 km2 (0.39 sq mi).
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The satellite sensor produces images of a particular location on the Earth twice a day.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] AVHRR and more recently the moderate-resolution imaging spectroradiometer (MODIS) are only two of many sensor systems used for Earth surface analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] In addition to the integration of time in environmental studies, GIS is also being explored for its ability to track and model the progress of humans throughout their daily routines.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] A concrete example of progress in this area is the recent release of time-specific population data by the U.S.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] In this data set, the populations of cities are shown for daytime and evening hours highlighting the pattern of concentration and dispersion generated by North American commuting patterns.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The manipulation and generation of data required to produce this data would not have been possible without GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Using models to project the data held by a GIS forward in time have enabled planners to test policy decisions using spatial decision support systems.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Tools and technologies emerging from the World Wide Web Consortium's Semantic Web are proving useful for data integration problems in information systems.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Correspondingly, such technologies have been proposed as a means to facilitate interoperability and data reuse among GIS applications and also to enable new analysis mechanisms.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Ontologies are a key component of this semantic approach as they allow a formal, machine-readable specification of the concepts and relationships in a given domain.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] This in turn allows a GIS to focus on the intended meaning of data rather than its syntax or structure.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Tentative ontologies have been developed in areas related to GIS applications, for example the hydrology ontology developed by the Ordnance Survey in the United Kingdom and the SWEET ontologies developed by NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Also, simpler ontologies and semantic metadata standards are being proposed by the W3C Geo Incubator Group to represent geospatial data on the web.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Recent research results in this area can be seen in the International Conference on Geospatial Semantics and the Terra Cognita – Directions to the Geospatial Semantic Web workshop at the International Semantic Web Conference.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] With the popularization of GIS in decision making, scholars have begun to scrutinize the social and political implications of GIS.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS can also be misused to distort reality for individual and political gain.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS technologies played a central role during the COVID-19 pandemic by enabling public health agencies and researchers to visualize and monitor disease spread in real time.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] The *Johns Hopkins University COVID-19 Dashboard* became one of the most widely cited GIS applications, demonstrating how web-based spatial data can inform policy and public awareness.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] It has been argued that the production, distribution, use, and representation of geographic information are largely related with the social context and has the potential to increase citizen trust in government.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Other related topics include discussion on copyright, privacy, and censorship.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] A more optimistic social approach to GIS adoption is to use it as a tool for public participation.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] At the end of the 20th century, GIS began to be recognized as tools that could be used in the classroom.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS seems to provide many advantages in teaching geography because it allows for analysis based on real geographic data and also helps raise research questions from teachers and students in the classroom.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] It also contributes to improvement in learning by developing spatial and geographical thinking and, in many cases, student motivation.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Courses in GIS are also offered by educational institutions.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS is proven as an organization-wide, enterprise and enduring technology that continues to change how local government operates.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS has been an important tool in archaeology since the early 1990s.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Surveys and documentation are important to preservation and archaeology, and GIS makes this research and fieldwork efficient and precise.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS is also used to help manage the conservation of cultural heritage sites.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] GIS helps conservation organizations monitor the impacts of development, conflict, and climate change on archaeological and other cultural resources.
[src:geospatial-gis/geographic-information-system-p02] Some public agencies use GIS software to assess the potential impacts of construction and other development and use these assessments in permitting and mitigation processes.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The **shapefile** format is a geospatial vector data format for geographic information system (GIS) software.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] It is developed and regulated by Esri as a mostly open specification for data interoperability among Esri and other GIS software products.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The shapefile format can spatially describe vector features: points, lines, and polygons, representing, for example, water wells, rivers, and lakes.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] Each item usually has attributes that describe it, such as *name* or *temperature*.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The shapefile format is a digital vector storage format for storing geographic location and associated attribute information.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] This format lacks the capacity to store topological information.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The shapefile format was introduced with ArcView GIS version 2 in the early 1990s.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] It is now possible to read and write geographical datasets using the shapefile format with a wide variety of software.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The shapefile format stores the geometry as primitive geometric shapes like points, lines, and polygons.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] These shapes, together with data attributes that are linked to each shape, create the representation of the geographic data.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The term "shapefile" is quite common, but the format consists of a collection of files with a common filename prefix, stored in the same directory.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The three *mandatory* files have filename extensions `.shp`, `.shx`, and `.dbf`.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The actual *shapefile* relates specifically to the `.shp` file, but alone is incomplete for distribution as the other supporting files are required.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] In line with the *ESRI Shapefile Technical Description*, legacy GIS software may expect that the filename prefix be limited to eight characters to conform to the DOS 8.3 filename convention, though modern software applications accept files with longer names.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] Shape format; the feature geometry itself.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] Shape index format; a positional index of the feature geometry to allow seeking forwards and backwards quickly.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] In each of the `.shp`, `.shx`, and `.dbf` files, the shapes in each file correspond to each other in sequence (i.e., the first record in the `.shp` file corresponds to the first record in the `.shx` and `.dbf` files, etc.).
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The `.shp` and `.shx` files have various fields with different endianness, so an implementer of the file formats must be very careful to respect the endianness of each field and treat it properly.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The main file (.shp) contains the geometry data.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] Geometry of a given feature is stored as a set of vector coordinates.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The binary file consists of a single fixed-length header followed by one or more variable-length records.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] Each of the variable-length records includes a record-header component and a record-contents component.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] A detailed description of the file format is given in the *ESRI Shapefile Technical Description*.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] This format should not be confused with the AutoCAD shape font source format, which shares the `.shp` extension.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The 2D axis ordering of coordinate data assumes a Cartesian coordinate system, using the order (X Y) or (Easting Northing).
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] This axis order is consistent for Geographic coordinate systems, where the order is similarly (longitude latitude).
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] Geometries may also support 3- or 4-dimensional Z and M coordinates, for elevation and measure, respectively.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] A Z-dimension stores the elevation of each coordinate in 3D space, which can be used for analysis or for visualisation of geometries using 3D computer graphics.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The user-defined M dimension can be used for one of many functions, such as storing linear referencing measures or relative time of a feature in 4D space.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The file then contains any number of variable-length records.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The variable-length record contents depend on the shape type, which must be either the shape type given in the file header or Null.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] Using this index, it is possible to seek backwards in the shapefile by, first, seeking backwards in the shape index (which is possible because it uses fixed-length records), then reading the record offset, and using that offset to seek to the correct position in the `.shp` file.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] It is also possible to seek forwards an arbitrary number of records using the same method.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] It is possible to generate the complete index file given a lone `.shp` file.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] However, since a shapefile is supposed to always contain an index, doing so counts as repairing a corrupt file.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] This file stores the attributes for each shape; it uses the dBase IV format.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The format is public knowledge, and has been implemented in many dBase clones known as xBase.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The open-source shapefile C library, for example, calls its format "xBase" even though it's plain dBase IV.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The names and values of attributes are not standardized, and will be different depending on the source of the shapefile.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] This is a binary spatial index file, which is used only by Esri software.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] However it has been reverse-engineered and documented by the open source community.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The 100-byte header is similar to the one in .shp.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] It is not currently implemented by other vendors.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The `.sbn` file is not strictly necessary, since the `.shp` file contains all of the information necessary to successfully parse the spatial data.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The shapefile format has a number of limitations.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The shapefile format does not have the ability to store topological relationships between shapes.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The ESRI ArcInfo coverages and many geodatabases do have the ability to store feature topology.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The size of both `.shp` and `.dbf` component files cannot exceed 2 GB (or 231 bytes) — around 70 million point features at best.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The maximum number of feature for other geometry types varies depending on the number of vertices used.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] The attribute database format for the `.dbf` component file is based on an older dBase standard.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] Because the shape type precedes each geometry record, a shapefile is technically capable of storing a mixture of different shape types.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] However, the specification states, "All the non-Null shapes in a shapefile are required to be of the same shape type." Therefore, this ability to mix shape types must be limited to interspersing null shapes with the single shape type declared in the file's header.
[src:geospatial-gis/shapefile] A shapefile must not contain both polyline and polygon data, for example, the descriptions for a well (point), a river (polyline), and a lake (polygon) would be stored in three separate datasets.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Complex issues arise in spatial analysis, many of which are neither clearly defined nor completely resolved, but form the basis for current research.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The most fundamental of these is the problem of defining the spatial location of the entities being studied.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Classification of the techniques of spatial analysis is difficult because of the large number of different fields of research involved, the different fundamental approaches which can be chosen, and the many forms the data can take.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial analysis began with early attempts at cartography and surveying.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Land surveying goes back to at least 1,400 B.C in Egypt: the dimensions of taxable land plots were measured with measuring ropes and plumb bobs.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Many fields have contributed to its rise in modern form.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Biology contributed through botanical studies of global plant distributions and local plant locations, ethological studies of animal movement, landscape ecological studies of vegetation blocks, ecological studies of spatial population dynamics, and the study of biogeography.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Epidemiology contributed with early work on disease mapping, notably John Snow's work of mapping an outbreak of cholera, with research on mapping the spread of disease and with location studies for health care delivery.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Statistics has contributed greatly through work in spatial statistics.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Economics has contributed notably through spatial econometrics.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Geographic information system is currently a major contributor due to the importance of geographic software in the modern analytic toolbox.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Remote sensing has contributed extensively in morphometric and clustering analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Computer science has contributed extensively through the study of algorithms, notably in computational geometry.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Mathematics continues to provide the fundamental tools for analysis and to reveal the complexity of the spatial realm, for example, with recent work on fractals and scale invariance.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Scientific modelling provides a useful framework for new approaches.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Many of these issues are active subjects of modern research.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Common errors often arise in spatial analysis, some due to the mathematics of space, some due to the particular ways data are presented spatially, some due to the tools which are available.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Census data, because it protects individual privacy by aggregating data into local units, raises a number of statistical issues.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The fractal nature of coastline makes precise measurements of its length difficult if not impossible.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A computer software fitting straight lines to the curve of a coastline, can easily calculate the lengths of the lines which it defines.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] However these straight lines may have no inherent meaning in the real world, as was shown for the coastline of Britain.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] These problems represent a challenge in spatial analysis because of the power of maps as media of presentation.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] When results are presented as maps, the presentation combines spatial data which are generally accurate with analytic results which may be inaccurate, leading to an impression that analytic results are more accurate than the data would indicate.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A boundary problem in analysis is a phenomenon in which geographical patterns are differentiated by the shape and arrangement of boundaries that are drawn for administrative or measurement purposes.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The boundary problem occurs because of the loss of neighbors in analyses that depend on the values of the neighbors.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] While geographic phenomena are measured and analyzed within a specific unit, identical spatial data can appear either dispersed or clustered depending on the boundary placed around the data.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In analysis with point data, dispersion is evaluated as dependent of the boundary.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In analysis with areal data, statistics should be interpreted based upon the boundary.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The modifiable areal unit problem (MAUP) is a source of statistical bias that can significantly impact the results of statistical hypothesis tests.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The MAUP affects results when point-based measures of spatial phenomena are aggregated into spatial partitions or *areal units* (such as regions or districts) as in, for example, population density or illness rates.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The resulting summary values (e.g., totals, rates, proportions, densities) are influenced by both the shape and scale of the aggregation unit.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For example, census data may be aggregated into county districts, census tracts, postcode areas, police precincts, or any other arbitrary spatial partition.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Thus, the results of data aggregation are dependent on the mapmaker's choice of which "modifiable areal unit" to use in their analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A census choropleth map calculating population density using state boundaries will yield radically different results from a map that calculates density based on county boundaries.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Furthermore, census district boundaries are also subject to change over time, meaning the MAUP must be considered when comparing past to current data.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The Modified Temporal Unit Problem (MTUP) is a source of statistical bias that occurs in time series and spatial analysis when using temporal data that has been aggregated into temporal units.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In such cases, choosing a temporal unit (e.g., days, months, years) can affect the analysis results and lead to inconsistencies or errors in statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The neighborhood effect averaging problem (NEAP) is a source of statistical bias that can significantly impact the results of statistical hypothesis tests.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It is caused by the influence of aggregating neighborhood-level phenomena on individuals when mobility-dependent exposures influence the phenomena.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The problem confounds the neighbourhood effect, which suggests that a person's neighborhood impacts their individual characteristics, such as health.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It relates to the boundary problem, in that delineated neighborhoods used for analysis may not fully account for an individual's activity space if the borders are permeable, and individual mobility crosses the boundaries.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The term was first coined by Mei-Po Kwan in 2018.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The travelling purchaser problem, the vehicle routing problem and the ring star problem are three generalizations of TSP.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The decision version of the TSP (where given a length *L*, the task is to decide whether the graph has a tour whose length is at most *L*) belongs to the class of NP-complete problems.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Thus, it is possible that the worst-case running time for any algorithm for the TSP increases superpolynomially (but no more than exponentially) with the number of cities.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The problem was first formulated in 1930 and is one of the most intensively studied problems in optimization.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It is used as a benchmark for many optimization methods.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Even though the problem is computationally difficult, many heuristics and exact algorithms are known, so that some instances with tens of thousands of cities can be solved completely, and even problems with millions of cities can be approximated within a small fraction of 1%.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For example, a study that measures the effect of a person's residential neighborhood on health outcomes may overlook environmental influences encountered while working, traveling, or engaging in activities elsewhere.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The term was coined by geographer Mei-Po Kwan in 2012.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In geometry, the Weber problem, named after Alfred Weber, is one of the most famous problems in location theory.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It requires finding a point in the plane that minimizes the sum of the transportation costs from this point to n destination points, where different destination points are associated with different costs per unit distance.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The Weber problem generalizes the geometric median, which assumes transportation costs per unit distance are the same for all destination points, and the problem of computing the Fermat point, the geometric median of three points.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For this reason it is sometimes called the Fermat–Weber problem, although the same name has also been used for the unweighted geometric median problem.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The Weber problem is in turn generalized by the attraction–repulsion problem, which allows some of the costs to be negative, so that greater distance from some points is better.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The definition of the spatial presence of an entity constrains the possible analysis which can be applied to that entity and influences the final conclusions that can be reached.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] While this property is fundamentally true of all analysis, it is particularly important in spatial analysis because the tools to define and study entities favor specific characterizations of the entities being studied.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Statistical techniques favor the spatial definition of objects as points because there are very few statistical techniques which operate directly on line, area, or volume elements.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Computer tools favor the spatial definition of objects as homogeneous and separate elements because of the limited number of database elements and computational structures available, and the ease with which these primitive structures can be created.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Tools for exploring spatial dependence include: spatial correlation, spatial covariance functions and semivariograms.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Methods for spatial interpolation include Kriging, which is a type of best linear unbiased prediction.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The topic of spatial dependence is of importance to geostatistics and spatial analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial dependency is the co-variation of properties within geographic space: characteristics at proximal locations appear to be correlated, either positively or negatively.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial dependency leads to the **spatial autocorrelation** problem in statistics since, like temporal autocorrelation, this violates standard statistical techniques that assume independence among observations.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For example, regression analyses that do not compensate for spatial dependency can have unstable parameter estimates and yield unreliable significance tests.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial regression models (see below) capture these relationships and do not suffer from these weaknesses.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It is also appropriate to view spatial dependency as a source of information rather than something to be corrected.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Locational effects also manifest as spatial heterogeneity, or the apparent variation in a process with respect to location in geographic space.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Unless a space is uniform and boundless, every location will have some degree of uniqueness relative to the other locations.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This affects the spatial dependency relations and therefore the spatial process.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial heterogeneity means that overall parameters estimated for the entire system may not adequately describe the process at any given location.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Like spatial autocorrelation, this can be a useful tool for spatial prediction.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In spatial modeling, the concept of spatial association allows the use of covariates in a regression equation to predict the geographic field and thus produce a map.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The second dimension of spatial association (SDA) reveals the association between spatial variables through extracting geographical information at locations outside samples.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] SDA effectively uses the missing geographical information outside sample locations in methods of the first dimension of spatial association (FDA), which explore spatial association using observations at sample locations.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In the field of public health surveillance, spatial analysis techniques have investigated topics such as the correlation between literacy rates and health insurance enrollment gaps.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial measurement scale is a persistent issue in spatial analysis; more detail is available at the modifiable areal unit problem (MAUP) topic entry.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Landscape ecologists developed a series of scale invariant metrics for aspects of ecology that are fractal in nature.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In more general terms, no scale independent method of analysis is widely agreed upon for spatial statistics.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial sampling involves determining a limited number of locations in geographic space for faithfully measuring phenomena that are subject to dependency and heterogeneity.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Dependency suggests that since one location can predict the value of another location, we do not need observations in both places.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] But heterogeneity suggests that this relation can change across space, and therefore we cannot trust an observed degree of dependency beyond a region that may be small.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Basic spatial sampling schemes include random, clustered and systematic.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] These basic schemes can be applied at multiple levels in a designated spatial hierarchy (e.g., urban area, city, neighborhood).
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It is also possible to exploit ancillary data, for example, using property values as a guide in a spatial sampling scheme to measure educational attainment and income.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial models such as autocorrelation statistics, regression and interpolation (see below) can also dictate sample design.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The fundamental issues in spatial analysis lead to numerous problems in analysis including bias, distortion and outright errors in the conclusions reached.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] These issues are often interlinked but various attempts have been made to separate out particular issues from each other.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In discussing the coastline of Britain, Benoit Mandelbrot showed that certain spatial concepts are inherently nonsensical despite presumption of their validity.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Lengths in ecology depend directly on the scale at which they are measured and experienced.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] So while surveyors commonly measure the length of a river, this length only has meaning in the context of the relevance of the measuring technique to the question under study.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The locational fallacy refers to error due to the particular spatial characterization chosen for the elements of study, in particular choice of placement for the spatial presence of the element.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial characterizations may be simplistic or even wrong.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Studies of humans often reduce the spatial existence of humans to a single point, for instance their home address.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This can easily lead to poor analysis, for example, when considering disease transmission which can happen at work or at school and therefore far from the home.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The spatial characterization may implicitly limit the subject of study.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For example, the spatial analysis of crime data has recently become popular but these studies can only describe the particular kinds of crime which can be described spatially.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This leads to many maps of assault but not to any maps of embezzlement with political consequences in the conceptualization of crime and the design of policies to address the issue.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This describes errors due to treating elements as separate 'atoms' outside of their spatial context.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The fallacy is about transferring individual conclusions to spatial units.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The ecological fallacy describes errors due to performing analyses on aggregate data when trying to reach conclusions on the individual units.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Errors occur in part from spatial aggregation.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For example, a pixel represents the average surface temperatures within an area.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Ecological fallacy would be to assume that all points within the area have the same temperature.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A mathematical space exists whenever we have a set of observations and quantitative measures of their attributes.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For example, we can represent individuals' incomes or years of education within a coordinate system where the location of each individual can be specified with respect to both dimensions.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The distance between individuals within this space is a quantitative measure of their differences with respect to income and education.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] However, in spatial analysis, we are concerned with specific types of mathematical spaces, namely, geographic space.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In geographic space, the observations correspond to locations in a spatial measurement framework that capture their proximity in the real world.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The locations in a spatial measurement framework often represent locations on the surface of the Earth, but this is not strictly necessary.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A spatial measurement framework can also capture proximity with respect to, say, interstellar space or within a biological entity such as a liver.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The fundamental tenet is Tobler's First Law of Geography: if the interrelation between entities increases with proximity in the real world, then representation in geographic space and assessment using spatial analysis techniques are appropriate.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The Euclidean distance between locations often represents their proximity, although this is only one possibility.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] There are an infinite number of distances in addition to Euclidean that can support quantitative analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For example, "Manhattan" (or "Taxicab") distances where movement is restricted to paths parallel to the axes can be more meaningful than Euclidean distances in urban settings.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In addition to distances, other geographic relationships such as connectivity**(e.g., the existence or degree of shared borders) and direction** can also influence the relationships among entities.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It is also possible to compute minimal cost paths across a cost surface; for example, this can represent proximity among locations when travel must occur across rugged terrain.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Urban and Regional Studies deal with large tables of spatial data obtained from censuses and surveys.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It is necessary to simplify the huge amount of detailed information in order to extract the main trends.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The factors, actually the eigenvectors, are orthogonal by construction, i.e. not correlated.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In most cases, the dominant factor (with the largest eigenvalue) is the Social Component, separating rich and poor in the city.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Since factors are not-correlated, other smaller processes than social status, which would have remained hidden otherwise, appear on the second, third, ... factors.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Factor analysis depends on measuring distances between observations : the choice of a significant metric is crucial.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The Euclidean metric (Principal Component Analysis), the Chi-Square distance (Correspondence Analysis) or the Generalized Mahalanobis distance (Discriminant Analysis) are among the more widely used.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] More complicated models, using communalities or rotations have been proposed.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Using multivariate methods in spatial analysis began really in the 1950s (although some examples go back to the beginning of the century) and culminated in the 1970s, with the increasing power and accessibility of computers.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In 1961, in a groundbreaking study, British geographers used FA to classify British towns.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Brian J Berry, at the University of Chicago, and his students made a wide use of the method, applying it to most important cities in the world and exhibiting common social structures.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The use of Factor Analysis in Geography, made so easy by modern computers, has been very wide but not always very wise.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Since the vectors extracted are determined by the data matrix, it is not possible to compare factors obtained from different censuses.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A solution consists in fusing together several census matrices in a unique table which, then, may be analyzed.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This, however, assumes that the definition of the variables has not changed over time and produces very large tables, difficult to manage.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A better solution, proposed by psychometricians, groups the data in a « cubic matrix », with three entries (for instance, locations, variables, time periods).
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A Three-Way Factor Analysis produces then three groups of factors related by a small cubic « core matrix ».
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This method, which exhibits data evolution over time, has not been widely used in geography.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In Los Angeles, however, it has exhibited the role, traditionally ignored, of Downtown as an organizing center for the whole city during several decades.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial autocorrelation statistics measure and analyze the degree of dependency among observations in a geographic space.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Classic spatial autocorrelation statistics include Moran's I , Geary's C , Getis's G and the standard deviational ellipse.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] These statistics require measuring a spatial weights matrix that reflects the intensity of the geographic relationship between observations in a neighborhood, e.g., the distances between neighbors, the lengths of shared border, or whether they fall into a specified directional class such as "west".
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Classic spatial autocorrelation statistics compare the spatial weights to the covariance relationship at pairs of locations.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial autocorrelation statistics such as Moran's I and Geary's C are global in the sense that they estimate the overall degree of spatial autocorrelation for a dataset.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The possibility of spatial heterogeneity suggests that the estimated degree of autocorrelation may vary significantly across geographic space.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] **Local spatial autocorrelation statistics** provide estimates disaggregated to the level of the spatial analysis units, allowing assessment of the dependency relationships across space.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] G statistics compare neighborhoods to a global average and identify local regions of strong autocorrelation.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Local versions of the I and C statistics are also available.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial heterogeneity is a property generally ascribed to a landscape or to a population.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It refers to the uneven distribution of various concentrations of each species within an area.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A landscape with spatial heterogeneity has a mix of concentrations of multiple species of plants or animals (biological), or of terrain formations (geological), or environmental characteristics (e.g. rainfall, temperature, wind) filling its area.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial interaction or "gravity models" estimate the flow of people, material or information between locations in geographic space.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] After specifying the functional forms of these relationships, the analyst can estimate model parameters using observed flow data and standard estimation techniques such as ordinary least squares or maximum likelihood.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Competing destinations versions of spatial interaction models include the proximity among the destinations (or origins) in addition to the origin-destination proximity; this captures the effects of destination (origin) clustering on flows.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial interpolation methods estimate the variables at unobserved locations in geographic space based on the values at observed locations.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Basic methods include inverse distance weighting: this attenuates the variable with decreasing proximity from the observed location.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Kriging is a more sophisticated method that interpolates across space according to a spatial lag relationship that has both systematic and random components.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This can accommodate a wide range of spatial relationships for the hidden values between observed locations.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Kriging provides optimal estimates given the hypothesized lag relationship, and error estimates can be mapped to determine if spatial patterns exist.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial regression methods capture spatial dependency in regression analysis, avoiding statistical problems such as unstable parameters and unreliable significance tests, as well as providing information on spatial relationships among the variables involved.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Depending on the specific technique, spatial dependency can enter the regression model as relationships between the independent variables and the dependent, between the dependent variables and a spatial lag of itself, or in the error terms.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] **Geographically weighted regression** (GWR) is a local version of spatial regression that generates parameters disaggregated by the spatial units of analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This allows assessment of the spatial heterogeneity in the estimated relationships between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The use of Bayesian hierarchical modeling in conjunction with Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods have recently shown to be effective in modeling complex relationships using Poisson-Gamma-CAR, Poisson-lognormal-SAR, or Overdispersed logit models.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Statistical packages for implementing such Bayesian models using MCMC include WinBugs, CrimeStat and many packages available via R programming language.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial stochastic processes, such as Gaussian processes are also increasingly being deployed in spatial regression analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Model-based versions of GWR, known as spatially varying coefficient models have been applied to conduct Bayesian inference.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial stochastic processes can become computationally effective using scalable Gaussian process models, such as Gaussian Predictive Processes and Nearest Neighbor Gaussian Processes (NNGP).
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] for representing and predicting geographic phenomena.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Examples of SNNs are the OSFA spatial neural networks, SVANNs and GWNNs.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial volatility models describe spatial or spatiotemporal dependence in the conditional variance of a process, extending the concept of Autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) from time series to spatial settings.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Such models account for the fact that variability at one location may be related to variability at neighbouring locations, as defined by a spatial weights matrix.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Sato and Matsuda (2017) proposed a spatial log-ARCH model as an alternative formulation.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial volatility models find applications in disciplines where risk or uncertainty propagate over space, including regional economics, environmental risk assessment, and financial networks.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A recent review summarises methodological developments, estimation strategies, and applications of spatial and spatiotemporal volatility models across disciplines.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial interaction models are aggregate and top-down: they specify an overall governing relationship for flow between locations.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This characteristic is also shared by urban models such as those based on mathematical programming, flows among economic sectors, or bid-rent theory.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] An alternative modeling perspective is to represent the system at the highest possible level of disaggregation and study the bottom-up emergence of complex patterns and relationships from behavior and interactions at the individual level.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Complex adaptive systems theory as applied to spatial analysis suggests that simple interactions among proximal entities can lead to intricate, persistent and functional spatial entities at aggregate levels.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Two fundamentally spatial simulation methods are cellular automata and agent-based modeling.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Cellular automata modeling imposes a fixed spatial framework such as grid cells and specifies rules that dictate the state of a cell based on the states of its neighboring cells.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] As time progresses, spatial patterns emerge as cells change states based on their neighbors; this alters the conditions for future time periods.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For example, cells can represent locations in an urban area and their states can be different types of land use.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Patterns that can emerge from the simple interactions of local land uses include office districts and urban sprawl.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Agent-based modeling uses software entities (agents) that have purposeful behavior (goals) and can react, interact and modify their environment while seeking their objectives.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Unlike the cells in cellular automata, simulysts can allow agents to be mobile with respect to space.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For example, one could model traffic flow and dynamics using agents representing individual vehicles that try to minimize travel time between specified origins and destinations.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] While pursuing minimal travel times, the agents must avoid collisions with other vehicles also seeking to minimize their travel times.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Cellular automata and agent-based modeling are complementary modeling strategies.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] They can be integrated into a common geographic automata system where some agents are fixed while others are mobile.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Calibration plays a pivotal role in both CA and ABM simulation and modelling approaches.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Initial approaches to CA proposed robust calibration approaches based on stochastic, Monte Carlo methods.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] ABM approaches rely on agents' decision rules (in many cases extracted from qualitative research base methods such as questionnaires).
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Recent Machine Learning Algorithms calibrate using training sets, for instance in order to understand the qualities of the built environment.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial analysis of a conceptual geological model is the main purpose of any MPS algorithm.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The method analyzes the spatial statistics of the geological model, called the training image, and generates realizations of the phenomena that honor those input multiple-point statistics.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] A recent MPS algorithm used to accomplish this task is the pattern-based method by Honarkhah.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In this method, a distance-based approach is employed to analyze the patterns in the training image.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This allows the reproduction of the multiple-point statistics, and the complex geometrical features of the training image.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Each output of the MPS algorithm is a realization that represents a random field.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Together, several realizations may be used to quantify spatial uncertainty.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] One of the recent methods is presented by Tahmasebi et al. uses a cross-correlation function to improve the spatial pattern reproduction.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] They call their MPS simulation method as the CCSIM algorithm.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This method is able to quantify the spatial connectivity, variability and uncertainty.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Furthermore, the method is not sensitive to any type of data and is able to simulate both categorical and continuous scenarios.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Geographic information systems (GIS) — a large domain that provides a variety of capabilities designed to capture, store, manipulate, analyze, manage, and present all types of geographical data — utilizes geospatial and hydrospatial analysis in a variety of contexts, operations and applications.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Geospatial and Hydrospatial analysis, using GIS, was developed for problems in the environmental and life sciences, in particular ecology, geology and epidemiology.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] It has extended to almost all industries including defense, intelligence, utilities, Natural Resources (i.e.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Oil and Gas, Forestry ... etc.), social sciences, medicine and Public Safety (i.e. emergency management and criminology), disaster risk reduction and management (DRRM), and climate change adaptation (CCA).
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial statistics typically result primarily from observation rather than experimentation.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Hydrospatial is particularly used for the aquatic side and the members related to the water surface, column, bottom, sub-bottom and the coastal zones.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] This reflects (and is reflected in) the use of the term spatial analysis within the Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC) "simple feature specifications".
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] For raster-based GIS, widely used in the environmental sciences and remote sensing, this typically means a range of actions applied to the grid cells of one or more maps (or images) often involving filtering and/or algebraic operations (map algebra).
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Descriptive statistics, such as cell counts, means, variances, maxima, minima, cumulative values, frequencies and a number of other measures and distance computations are also often included in this generic term spatial analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Spatial analysis includes a large variety of statistical techniques (descriptive, exploratory, and explanatory statistics) that apply to data that vary spatially and which can vary over time.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Some more advanced statistical techniques include Getis-ord Gi* or Anselin Local Moran's I which are used to determine clustering patterns of spatially referenced data.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Geospatial and Hydrospatial analysis goes beyond 2D and 3D mapping operations and spatial statistics.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Traditionally geospatial and hydrospatial computing has been performed primarily on personal computers (PCs) or servers.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Due to the increasing capabilities of mobile devices, however, geospatial computing in mobile devices is a fast-growing trend.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The portable nature of these devices, as well as the presence of useful sensors, such as Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) receivers and barometric pressure sensors, make them useful for capturing and processing geospatial and hydrospatial information in the field.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In addition to the local processing of geospatial information on mobile devices, another growing trend is cloud-based geospatial computing.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In this architecture, data can be collected in the field using mobile devices and then transmitted to cloud-based servers for further processing and ultimate storage.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] In a similar manner, geospatial and hydrospatial information can be made available to connected mobile devices via the cloud, allowing access to vast databases of geospatial and hydrospatial information anywhere where a wireless data connection is available.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Geographic information systems (GIS) and the underlying geographic information science that advances these technologies have a strong influence on spatial analysis.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] The increasing ability to capture and handle geographic data means that spatial analysis is occurring within increasingly data-rich environments.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] Geographic data capture systems include remotely sensed imagery, environmental monitoring systems such as intelligent transportation systems, and location-aware technologies such as mobile devices that can report location in near-real time.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-analysis] GIS provide platforms for managing these data, computing spatial relationships such as distance, connectivity and directional relationships between spatial units, and visualizing both the raw data and spatial analytic results within a cartographic context.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] A **spatial reference system** (**SRS**) or **coordinate reference system** (**CRS**) is a framework used to precisely measure locations on, or relative to, the surface of Earth as coordinates.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] It is thus the application of the abstract mathematics of coordinate systems and analytic geometry to geographic space.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] A particular SRS specification (for example, "Universal Transverse Mercator WGS 84 Zone 16N") comprises a choice of Earth ellipsoid, horizontal datum, map projection (except in the geographic coordinate system), origin point, and unit of measure.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] Thousands of coordinate systems have been specified for use around the world or in specific regions and for various purposes, necessitating transformations between different SRS.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] Although they date to the Hellenistic period, spatial reference systems are now a crucial basis for the sciences and technologies of Geoinformatics, including cartography, geographic information systems, surveying, remote sensing, and civil engineering.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] The above refers to locations directly on the surface of the earth.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] Information on elevation may also be specified, via a vertical reference frame, so-called vertical CRS, or an integrated 3D CRS.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] Terminology in this area is evolving in line with increasing technical sophistication in measurement.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] , because they are based on the center of mass.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] that models the surface of Earth (or more commonly, a large region thereof) as a plane, measuring locations from an arbitrary origin point along x and y axes more or less aligned with the cardinal directions.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] to create a planar surface from the curved Earth surface.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] Such SRSs are generally defined and used strategically in their target regions to minimize the distortions inherent to projections for specific use cases.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] (2-D or 3-D) that is created bespoke for a small area, often a single engineering project, over which the curvature of the Earth can be safely approximated as flat without significant distortion.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] These may or may not be aligned with a standard projected coordinate system.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] are a type of local coordinate system used in aviation and marine vehicles.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] This does not carry information about localization of a point on the surface of the earth, but elevation relative to the surface of the earth, importantly including specification of what zero elevation is.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] Combines a geographic or projected coordinate system with a vertical reference frame to provide a full parametrization of locations on or near the surface of the earth relative to a chosen zero elevation level.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] These standards acknowledge that standard reference systems also exist for time (e.g.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] These may be combined with a spatial reference system to form a *compound coordinate system* for representing three-dimensional and/or spatio-temporal locations.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] There are also internal systems for measuring location within the context of an object, such as the rows and columns of pixels in a raster image, Linear referencing measurements along linear features (e.g., highway mileposts), and systems for specifying location within moving objects such as ships.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] The latter two are often classified as subcategories of engineering coordinate systems.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] The goal of any spatial reference system is to create a common reference frame in which locations can be measured precisely and consistently as coordinates, which can then be shared unambiguously, so that any recipient can identify the same location that was originally intended by the originator.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] A **Spatial Reference System Identifier** (**SRID**) is a unique value used to unambiguously identify projected, unprojected, and local spatial coordinate system definitions.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] These coordinate systems form the heart of all GIS applications.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] Virtually all major spatial vendors have created their own SRID implementation or refer to those of an authority, such as the EPSG Geodetic Parameter Dataset.
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] SRIDs are typically associated with a well-known text (WKT) string definition of the coordinate system (SRTEXT, above).
[src:geospatial-gis/spatial-reference-system] SRID values associated with spatial data can be used to constrain spatial operations — for instance, spatial operations cannot be performed between spatial objects with differing SRIDs in some systems, or trigger coordinate system transformations between spatial objects in others.
